Frosting and icing are often switched for each other. Americans tend to use the term "frosting" to mean the creamy, sugary substance that covers a cake, while individuals in other English speaking areas tend to use the term "icing". In the U.S.A., "frosting" commonly refers to the icing that is spread over the cake, while "icing" usually refers to decorative icing, such as piped borders and icing roses. There is different types of frosting (which can also double as filling where needed):
Fondant - Fondant is also called sugar paste. Fondant is an icing sugar dough that can be worked in much the same way as pie dough. Fondant can be rolled into smooth sheets and draped over cakes, making a smooth, flawless finish. Ganache - Ganache is a velvety smooth frosting. It is prepared by melting either dark or white chocolate, then mixing it with heavy cream. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Gumpaste - Gumpaste is an edible, clay-like dough. It is prepared by combining glycerin, gum Arabic, and icing sugar. Gumpaste is used to mold edible flowers and designs. Gum paste can also be rolled exceedingly thin and used to make intricate ribbons and lacework, as well as delicate flower petals. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Marzipan - Marzipan is a doughy almond substance. It is made from the identical ingredients as almond paste, though marzipan has more sugar, fewer almonds, and has a smoother consistency. Marzipan is often used for modeling cake decorations, and as a base covering underneath fondant. Piping - Piping is a decorating method where a decorating bag or tube is filled with icing and fitted with a decorating tip. Piping takes place when the bag is gently squeezed to make shaped dots and ribbons of icing to adorn cakes and other baked goods. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/09/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/09/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Royal Icing - Royal icing is a sweet white icing that is prepared by whipping icing sugar with either fresh egg whites or dried egg whites and meringue powder. Royal icing makes crisp icing borders. It is perfect for piping intricate writing, borders, scrollwork, and lacework on cakes. Royal icing dries very hard and preserves indefinitely if stored in a cool, dry place, but is vulnerable to softening and drooping in high humidity. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Learn-About-Common-Cake-Decorating-Terms-Step-7Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
